```json
{
  "global": "Use ray geometry to determine how surface ripples distort the Moon's reflection differently in vertical vs horizontal directions at grazing incidence (3° above horizon), deriving the magnification ratio.",
  "subtasks": [
    {
      "subtask": "Establish coordinate system and ray geometry for the reflection setup",
      "atomics": [
        "Define coordinate system: z vertical, x toward/away from observer, y horizontal perpendicular to x",
        "Position Moon at angle α = 3° above horizon",
        "Describe incident ray direction traveling downward at 3° from horizontal",
        "Express reflected ray direction via law of reflection on ocean surface"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Analyze how surface slopes affect reflected ray direction",
      "atomics": [
        "Compute the effect of slope ∂z/∂x (vertical ripples perpendicular to line of sight) on normal vector",
        "Calculate reflected ray deviation for small slope ∂z/∂x using law of reflection r = d - 2(d·n)n",
        "Compute the effect of slope ∂z/∂y (horizontal ripples parallel to line of sight) on normal vector",
        "Calculate reflected ray deviation for small slope ∂z/∂y similarly"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Derive magnification factors for vertical and horizontal displacement at grazing incidence",
      "atomics": [
        "Show that vertical angular spread from slope ∂z/∂x varies as 1/sin(α) × (slope variation)",
        "Show that horizontal angular spread from slope ∂z/∂y varies as constant × (slope variation)",
        "Establish that magnification factor for vertical is M_v = 1/sin(α)",
        "Establish that magnification factor for horizontal is M_h = 1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Compute the ratio of magnifications and numerical result",
      "atomics": [
        "Calculate ratio r = M_v / M_h = (1/sin(α)) / 1 = 1/sin(α)",
        "Evaluate 1/sin(3°) using sin(3°) ≈ 0.0523",
        "Obtain r ≈ 19.08",
        "Round to nearest whole number: r = 19"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "global_atomics": [
    "Verify that grazing incidence is the key physical regime enabling magnification",
    "Confirm that ripples with isotropic slope statistics create anisotropic image distortion due to viewing angle"
  ],
  "gold_actions": {
    "global": "Compute 1/sin(3°) where the grazing angle 3° creates vertical magnification relative to horizontal magnification at ocean reflection.",
    "subtasks": [
      {
        "subtask": "Establish the physics setup with grazing incidence geometry",
        "atomics": [
          "Set up spherical coordinates with Moon at angle 3° above ocean horizon, observer far from surface",
          "Define incident ray as traveling at 3° below horizontal (toward ocean)",
          "State reflected ray also travels at 3° above horizontal (back to observer)"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Apply reflection law to show slope sensitivity",
        "atomics": [
          "For surface slope ε in x-direction: reflected ray tilts by ~2ε in vertical plane",
          "For surface slope ε in y-direction: reflected ray tilts by ~2ε in y-direction",
          "Show that angular spread magnification differs between directions at grazing angle"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Derive the grazing incidence magnification formula",
        "atomics": [
          "At angle α from horizontal, vertical displacement scales as 1/sin(α) relative to surface height variation",
          "Horizontal displacement scales as 1 (no grazing magnification)",
          "Therefore vertical-to-horizontal magnification ratio M = 1/sin(α)"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Calculate numerical result for α = 3 degrees",
        "atomics": [
          "Compute sin(3°) = sin(π/60 rad) = 0.052336",
          "Calculate 1/sin(3°) = 1/0.052336 = 19.081",
          "Round 19.081 to nearest integer: 19"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "global_atomics": [
      "Recognize that cot(3°) ≈ 19 is equivalent formula confirming result",
      "Verify that answer makes physical sense: grazing geometry amplifies vertical over horizontal by factor ~19"
    ]
  }
}
```

FINAL ANSWER: 19
